title: rethinking of how calendar events are fetched
message:
rethinking of how calendar events are fetched

- functional goodness for processing (hypothetically more amenable to testing)
- at the top of the hour, we don't just re-layout, we read the whole damn calendar (hopefully)
- the layout optimizer now runs on the same background thread as the calendar fetcher, not on the UI thread
- the ClockState observers are still (hypothetically) pinged on the UI thread

Much testing is now necessary, but the structure looks good. We'll deal with functional-reactive stuff later on, if ever.

title: crash bug on the phone side fixed (maybe)
message:
crash bug on the phone side fixed (maybe)

Seems that when Android is trying to clean things up, it starts killing things left and right, and WatchCalendarService was blown away, generating a user-visible popup that it died, while other things killed at the same time died cleanly. Hypothesis: this is because the CalendarFetcher thread was still running. Added code to onDestroy() to kill that off.

title: Android 4.2 is the minimum API we can do
message:
Android 4.2 is the minimum API we can do

We use the GridLayout, which requires Android 4.0 and nano-time, which requires Android 4.2. We don't *really* need nano-time (it's only used to precisely measure frame rate reporting), but 4.2 seems like a more reasonable minimum than 4.4.

title: moved notification from redrawInternal to the slow redraw

moved notification from redrawInternal to the slow redraw
